Likewise, we recommended that management initiate the required documentation to convey and transfer the ownership of the school building to DHVSU and properly derecognize the same from the books of the municipality.

We recommended the following courses of action:
The Municipal Treasurer
Prepare a stratified schedule of “presumptive income level” to approximate the gross receipt of each business classification for every tax period;
Require all persons, who are granted a permit to conduct an activity or business and who are subject to payment of business tax to submit a certified photocopy of their income tax returns (ITR) on or before April 30 of each year and collect any tax deficiency, if any, including interest at the rate of ten percent (10%) corresponding to the two percent (2%) per month from January to May. Otherwise, enforce the corresponding penalty for non-compliance therewith;
Enjoin business establishments to pay taxes prior to retirement/closure;
Collect the tax deficiency from the concerned business entities; and
Enforce other remedies to ensure that the correct amount of fees and taxes are collected.
The designated Business Permit and Licensing Officer ensure that applicants, (i) for newly started businesses or renewal of existing permits, submit a complete set of all documentary requirements in securing permits and licenses prior to the approval of the Local Chief Executive; and (ii) declare the correct amount of gross sales in their application consistent with the provision of the Updated Revenue Ordinance.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:

Municipal Engineer, being the building official, to inform all applicants of building permit of their responsibilities after the completion of the structure which include, among others, the filing of a sworn declaration of the true value of the structure;

Municipal Assessor to declare all identified undeclared property in the name of the defaulting owner, if known, or against an unknown owner, as the case may be, and assess the property for taxation in accordance with laws, rules and regulations;

Municipal Treasurer to (i) ensure that the Municipal Accountant will be furnished with a copy of complete reports of collections from the Provincial Government of Pampanga (PGP); and (ii) regularly prepare and issue the necessary notice of delinquency and demand letters to delinquent taxpayers; and

Municipal Accountant to (a) secure a report of RPT collected by the PGP every year-end as the basis for the recognition of Receivables and Income accruing to the Municipality; (b) ensure that RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred Charges are duly adjusted upon receipt/remittance of Municipal share from the PGP; and (c) recognize in the books all adjusting and correcting entries.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

prioritize the creation of the mandatory positions required by R.A. No. 10121 and NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC JMC No. 2014-1 for the effective and efficient discharge of the duties and responsibilities of the LDRRMO;

ensure that any change in the annual budget is supported with valid authority and documentation pursuant to Section 321 of R.A. No. 7160 and Section 454(2)(b) of its IRR;

regularly update the LDRRMFIP, thru the LDRRMO Head, on the effects of any changes thereto in accordance with Item 6.2 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013;

adhere consistently with the processes and documentary requirements stated in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and the IRR of R.A. No. 9184 thru the BAC;

prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV), thru the Head of the Accounting Unit, to reclassify the affected equipment in their proper asset accounts pursuant to Item 5.1.7 of COA Circular 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012, as follows:

We recommended that the:
end-user of the goods needed to combat COVID-19 (i) conduct initial survey on the prevailing prices of drugs, medicines, and medical devices; and (ii) apply DOH issuances on suggested retail price granted to certain goods prior to the preparation of purchase request;
Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) comply with the mandatory documentation of procurement proceeding and thereafter, ensure that resolutions recommending award are reviewed to avoid conflicting details thereon;
Municipal Accountant (i) coordinate with the BAC in the submission of the required documents to the Office of the Auditor for further evaluation; (ii) ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payment to substantiate the regularity of claims; and (iii) prepare a note to disclosure in the financial statements the status of the receipt and issuance of in-kind donation; and
Management install an effective and efficient internal control over the receipt and issuance of in-kind donation in conformity with COA Circular Nos. 2014-002 and 2020-009.
Management Comment:	The BAC and end-users positively responded to comply with the recommendations. On the other hand, management agreed to install an effective and efficient internal control over the receipt and issuance of in-kind donations.

