We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 
(a)augment, as far as possible, the composition of the inventory committee to expedite the completion of the physical inventory process and pave the way for the preparation of Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) that is duly reconciled with the accounting and property records and submission to the Auditor’s Office; 
(b) require the Municipal Accountant and the designated Property Officer to
(i) continue the provision of subsidiary ledgers for PPE items by aiming for the full completion of the current and a percentage of recent year’s acquisition until all PPE items are covered; 
(ii) reconcile the respective records of the Municipal Accountant and the designated Property Officer relative to the PPE balances; 
(c)create an appraisal 
committee for the un-booked parcels of land and record the same under the PPE account; and 
(d) require the Municipal Treasury, Supply Officer and the Municipal Assessor to ascertain the status of parcels of land owned by the agency with titling issues and work for the titling thereof in the name of the Municipality of Apalit, assuming funds have been provided thereof.

We recommended that the:
(a) Inventory Committee mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments, as far as feasible, to facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items and in the event that documents as costing basis are no longer available, consider the fair value thereof as point of reference pursuant to PPSAS 17; 
(b) General Services Officer initiate the preparation and maintenance of Property Cards, starting with current and recent year’s acquisitions until all PPE items are covered;  
(c) Accountant and General Services Officer strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting, the property and actual inventory results; 
(d) coordinate with the Land Registration Authority (LRA) and seek technical assistance, if necessary, to be able to pinpoint the exact location of the lots tagged under the name of the Municipality as basis for the subsequent actions to be taken thereto; 
(e) for lots ascertained to be owned by the Municipality, request the Assessor to undertake appraisal thereof as basis for recognition and valuation in the books and for the initiation of efforts in the titling of the same; and 
(f) secure a copy of the deed of donation from PENRO to serve as the supporting document in the recording of the donated equipment.

We recommended that the Members of the Local School Board:

prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;

request for inputs from the DepEd official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;

maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the PPAs, and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprograming, if necessary; and

submit above-cited lacking documents and henceforth, comply with the required documentation for similar transactions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive and the MENRO 
(a) vigorously seek the approval of the plan from the National Solid Waste Management Commission; 
(b) strengthen, within the Municipality’s resources, the present organizational structure and manpower complement of the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Office so that the Municipality may be able to implement the five basic environmental laws on preserving and protecting the environment required under R.A. No. 9003; (c)involve closely the Barangay officials and civic leaders in the strict implementation on the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign at the household level on the ordinances issued by the Municipality; 
(d) seek the help of private companies/ organizations in the conduct of a more aggressive and intensive information campaign on the proper segregation of waste and “no littering” policies; and (e) formulate solid waste management programs that would encourage and motivate the public to give their cooperation and full support.
